      <wiki:abstract>
	<p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><i><b>Throw Momma from the Train</b></i> is a 1987 American <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_comedy" title="Black comedy">black comedy</a> film. It was inspired by the 1951 <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_Hitchcock" title="Alfred Hitchcock">Alfred Hitchcock</a> thriller <i><a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strangers_on_a_Train_(film)" title="Strangers on a Train (film)">Strangers on a Train</a></i>, which also plays a role in the film. The 1987 film's title comes from the 1956 hit song, <i><a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mama_From_The_Train" title="Mama From The Train">Mama From the Train (A Kiss, A Kiss)</a></i> written by <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irving_Gordon" title="Irving Gordon">Irving Gordon</a> and sung by <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patti_Page" title="Patti Page">Patti Page</a>.</p>
	<p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><i>Throw Momma from the Train</i> stars <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billy_Crystal" title="Billy Crystal">Billy Crystal</a>, <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Danny_DeVito" title="Danny DeVito">Danny DeVito</a> (who also directed), <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anne_Ramsey" title="Anne Ramsey">Anne Ramsey</a>, <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kim_Greist" title="Kim Greist">Kim Greist</a>, <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rob_Reiner" title="Rob Reiner">Rob Reiner</a>, <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Branford_Marsalis" title="Branford Marsalis">Branford Marsalis</a>, and <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kate_Mulgrew" title="Kate Mulgrew">Kate Mulgrew</a>, with a cameo appearance from <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oprah_Winfrey" title="Oprah Winfrey">Oprah Winfrey</a>. The film received mixed to positive reviews but was a major commercial success. Anne Ramsey was singled out for praise and her portrayal of the maniacal and overbearing Mrs. Lift and received an <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_Awards" title="Academy Awards">Academy Award</a> nomination for <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Supporting_Actress" title="Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress">Best Supporting Actress</a>.</p>
	<h2 xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"> <span class="mw-headline" id="Plot">Plot</span></h2>
      </wiki:abstract>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Larry Donner is a struggling writer who teaches a creative writing class at a <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Community_college" title="Community college">community college</a>. Larry feels anger and resentment towards his ex-wife, Margaret (Mulgrew), who has stolen his book and had it <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Published" title="Published">published</a> in her name. The book has become a smashing success and has propelled her to undeserved wealth and fame, including the chance to promote the book <i>Hot Fire</i> on <i><a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Oprah_Winfrey_Show" title="The Oprah Winfrey Show">The Oprah Winfrey Show</a></i>. Frustration caused by this plagiarism leads him to experience severe <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Writer%27s_block" title="Writer's block">writer's block</a> and distances him from his girlfriend, Beth (<a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kim_Greist" title="Kim Greist">Kim Greist</a>).</p>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Owen Lift is a student in Donner's writing class, but a rather incompetent writer. He is a middle aged timid man who lives with his overbearing, abusive mother (Anne Ramsey). He dreams of killing her, but turns spineless whenever she <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domestic_abuse" title="Domestic abuse">abuses</a> him.</p>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Owen goes to Larry seeking advice concerning his writing. Larry advises Owen to go see an Alfred Hitchcock film to gain some insight into <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plot_(narrative)" title="Plot (narrative)">plot</a> development. Owen also overhears Larry exclaiming that he wished his ex-wife were dead. Owen goes to see <i><a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strangers_on_a_Train_(film)" title="Strangers on a Train (film)">Strangers on a Train</a></i>, a movie in which two strangers meet on a train and one proposes a plot to commit a murder for each other. The murderer's lack of connection to the victim and the other person's ability to establish a perfect <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alibi" title="Alibi">alibi</a> at the time of the murder will, in theory, allow each to get away with murder.</p>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">When a news story appears announcing Margaret's disappearance from a <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cruise_ship" title="Cruise ship">cruise ship</a>, Owen comes to Larry and tells him that he has killed Margaret and that Larry now "owes" him the murder of his mother. Larry, realizing he is the primary suspect, stays with Owen and his mother in an attempt to hide from <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Detective" title="Detective">Detective</a> DeBenedetto (<a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bruce_Kirby_(actor)" title="Bruce Kirby (actor)">Bruce Kirby</a>), who has been assigned to bring Larry in for questioning. Larry meets Mrs. Lift, and despite her foul treatment of him, refuses to kill her. Eventually, when Mrs. Lift drives Owen to the breaking point, Larry finally relents and agrees to go through with the murder.</p>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Larry first attempts <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Suffocating" title="Suffocating">suffocating</a> the sleeping Mrs. Lift with a pillow, but he is scared away when he sees her eyes are open. A second attempt involved Larry pushing Mrs. Lift down the basement staircase through a door Owen loosens before going bowling (his alibi). Mrs. Lift, despite Larry's warning, punches the door but it doesn't fall. When Larry tests the door it comes loose and he and the door fall into the <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basement" title="Basement">basement</a>, knocking Larry <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unconscious" title="Unconscious">unconscious</a>. Owen returns home, and Mrs. Lift tells him Larry is dead, mocking him at the same time. Enraged, Owen tries to kill her himself by blowing a trumpet in her ear to give her a heart attack. The noise wakes Larry up, but only angers Mrs. Lift.</p>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">The next day a newsflash announces a bounty on Larry's head and Mrs. Lift, believing Larry to be a murderer, attempts to call the police. Larry rips the phone wire apart and heads for the train station to catch a train to <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mexico" title="Mexico">Mexico</a>. Surprisingly, Owen and Mrs. Lift accompany him so as to avoid having to lie for him. During the journey, Larry's patience with Mrs. Lift reaches its <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pinnacle" title="Pinnacle">pinnacle</a> when she unintentionally gives him advice on writing. Larry follows her out of the compartment after telling Owen that he accepts Owen's offer and intends to kill her. Owen however has second thoughts and gives chase to the end of the train. In the ensuing fight, Mrs. Lift almost falls off the train but is saved by Larry and Owen. Owen thus earns his mother's genuine love and respect but Mrs. Lift angrily kicks Larry off the moving train causing him to fall onto the railway and break his leg.</p>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Margaret is later discovered alive after being rescued by a <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynesia" title="Polynesia">Polynesian</a> <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisherman" title="Fisherman">fisherman</a>, whom she ends up marrying. Larry, seeing this on the news in a hospital, realizes that Owen didn't actually kill her but she had simply fallen overboard. Owen lied so as not to risk Larry going back on their "deal". To Larry's annoyance, Margaret's accident is only going to make her richer as she has sold the movie rights of the accident.</p>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">A year later, Larry is just finishing writing a book about his experiences with Owen and his mother entitled <i>Throw Momma from the Train</i>. Owen visits and informs him that his mother has died (of <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_causes" title="Natural causes">natural causes</a>) and that he is going to New York for the release of his own book. Unfortunately, Owen reveals that it is also about their experiences together. Thinking his book has been scooped, an enraged Larry proceeds to strangle him. He stops when Owen shows him a published copy of the book. It's a children's pop-up book called <i>Momma, Owen, and Owen's Friend Larry</i> with the story drastically altered to be suitable for children.</p>
